Background

9/16/21 update: Bob changed a few things from previous run since there were some errors.

In this document we run scenarios and show results from these runs. This work reads in two functions which initialize and high and low risk population. The low risk population is subject to a lower risk of infection initially. The high risk population has a higher ARI. The overall ARI is determined based on the TB prevalence and the work of Dodd et al. We calculate the number of infections these individuals have by age group and TB prevalence.

The second step is to generate new infections over a one year time period and then deterministically creates active cases of disease using prespecified progression rates that are a function of the number of infections an individual has.

Simulation Scenarios

We consider a set of prevalence values and associated ARI. We consider two scenarios about the population mixing: homogeneous mixing or a high and low risk exposure groups.

TB progression assumptions

We consider two assumptions around TB progression. The first scenario assumes stable protection from prior infections such that the risk of progress for the first infection is 4% and subsequent reinfections only have a 1% risk of progression. The second scenario assumes that there is protection, but that it wanes with an increasing number of infections (Ackley assumption).

Initializing the population

We also show the total number of infections and total number of times individuals have been infected by risk category.

We can also consider the number of infections individuals have by prevalence and risk category.

New cases generated over one year

We now generate cases over a one year period. All infected individuals with no reinfection in this year have a 0.00075 probability of progressing to active disease. Individuals with a first infection have a 0.04 probability of progressing. Those with a new re-infection follow the probability of progressing determine by either Ackley or assuming there is constant 75% protection from progressing, independent of the number of prior infections.

We can calculate the following statistics (the first 6 only apply to the mixing scenarios):

  • Cases from first infection, low risk
  • Cases from reinfection, low risk
  • Total cases, low risk
  • Cases from first infection, high risk
  • Cases from reinfection, high risk
  • Total cases, high risk
  • Cases from old infection (all in high risk)
  • Total cases
  • percent cases from first infection
  • percent cases from old infection
  • Corrected prevalence (=1.66*smear positive prevalence)
  • Incidence (per 100000)
  • Implied duration (=prev/Inc)
  • Reproductive number for infection (= #new infections/corrected prevalence)
  • Reproductive number for disease (= #ATB from new infections/corrected prevalence)
